I used the global terrorism database for research (https://www.start.umd.edu/gtd/). There have been only 2 attacks on federal installations resulting in 10+ fatalities in the last 52 years (Pentagon 2001 and Oklahoma City 1995). That is roughly a 2/52 or a 1/26 chance (3.8%) this will occur in any given year. None have occurred in the last 20 years. Significant security measures are in place to prevent large-scale fatalities like these from happening since these two attacks. Many groups still possess the intent, but very few possess the capability. There were less than 20 attacks/incidents (on any location) resulting in 10+ casualties during the same time period (50+ years). Most attacks occurred at Religious Sites or schools, not federal institutions - most likely because of high security at most federal institutions. Attackers would likely choose a site with little to no security IOT achieve similar results and media coverage. Unsuccessful attempts would bring less media attention - assuming that is the goal. This could still occur but I give it a very low chance that it will happen in the next six months.

I agree with the analysis by @Jmillim36 Go with the base rate and assume that over time our law enforcement investigators are getting better at foiling any plots. The only thing I would add is that the media tends to sensationalize these small-probability events, so the perception gets distorted and people view the probability as higher than it actually is. If someone is a federal worker they are far more likely to be killed by things like poorly-stacked materials in a supply room or chemicals used in the construction of their federal building than a terrorist. And yet what's salient in our minds is federal facilities being attacked, due to availability bias. Good paper here by Harvard professors Cass Sunstein and Richard Zeckhauser on the subject: https://heep.hks.harvard.edu/files/heep/files/dp2_zeckhauser-sunstein.pdf

Given a base rate of just .005% (see below), I assume a heightened threat environment between now and February 1st, 2023 where the probability of a mass attack on a federal facility increases 3 to 4 times higher than the base rate given increased tensions due to possibility of a Trump indictment, the upcoming midterm elections, and the anniversary of the January 6th attack. This results in just a 2% chance of an attack on a Federal facility that results in 10 or more fatalities.

I believe the potential for political violence to be very high but am starting with a low forecast due to the limited scope of the question: does not include assassinations of individuals (high likelihood), does not include attacks on city, county, or state facilities (high likelihood), and requires 10 fatalities (a high bar). If the scope of the question was broadened to include these cases, my forecast would be 70%.

People almost always talk about what they want to do, and the FBI will almost always hear it.

Attacks on federal facilities are fairly rare. To have ten fatalities would be a major attack in a sense. Something like the Oklahoma city bombing seems too large to happen today, in light of precautions put in place after 9/11. Most likely, it would probably be a shooting attack, but to have 10 fatalities would seem like a lot, given there is security at most of these buildings.

Domestic security has been determined by the ICs to be a significant domain of US attention. Given that domestic terror has been prioritized for attention over the next decade, counter-terror assessments along with concomitant responses remain on the security radar. While domestic threats are becoming normalized by the extreme right in the US, large or small scale attacks resulting in fatalities at Federal facilities are likely benign despite the destabilizing nature of political instability. Security mechanisms within the US are sufficiently robust to counter such threats an makes events such as these highly unlikely.

Let's assume given @Aaron1647217253/@Azzza link, the base rate of an attack on a federal facility is one every 2.4 years regardless of fatality. Adjusting with Laplace, I assume 57% of these cases ends in casualties of 10 or more. So if there is 5 months left (converted to years) divided by the average of 2.4 years, times 50%. That's 19%. Multiply by 57% chance it's over 10 deaths. Result is 11%.

In 2001-2013, there were 4 attacks on federal facilities resulting in 10 or more fatalities (one was 9/11). See https://www.secretservice.gov/sites/default/files/2020-04/Attacks_on_Federal_Government_2001-2013.pdf#page25
